                    <item>
              <title>To tweet or not to tweet? A phenomenological enquiry into the disposition of higher education lecturers towards the adoption of Twitter practices by Helen Crump</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/8217</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/8217</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>A dissertation submitted in partial fulfilment of the requirements for the degree of Masters in Technology, Learning, Innovation and Change by Helen Crump. St. Angela&rsquo;s College, Sligo. Awarded by the National University of Ireland, Galway, June 2012</p>
<p>This work is licensed under a <a href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 3.0 Unported License</a></p>
<p>This has been submitted as an OER within the OLDSMOOC project because it was used by Jane Challinor and myself&nbsp; to provide real context to the scenario building phase of our design project, and because the interviews with Higher Education lecturers were used to develop personas for the design too.</p>
<p><strong>Abstract:</strong></p>
<p>This phenomenological enquiry into lecturers&rsquo; disposition towards the adoption of the disruptive Web 2.0 technology Twitter comprises in-depth interviews with five lecturers in Irish higher education. The enquiry views Twitter as a digital literacy practice and takes a New Literacy Studies perspective to position Twitter as a social practice. Disposition is considered in terms of Bourdieu&rsquo;s contextual disposition.</p>
<p>The enquiry reveals the disruptive affects to long-standing knowledge-making practices and analysis of data, by a phenomenological condensation of meaning method, reveals a range of dispositions amongst the research sample lecturers towards the adoption of Twitter. Analysis suggests that the research sample lecturers are disposed towards its adoption if it affords congruence with the purpose of their practice and the values and beliefs upon which this is based, as well as with their personal beliefs and values too. Nonetheless, as a social practice, the adoption of Twitter does not go undisputed.</p>
<p>Keywords: Twitter, Web 2.0, disruptive technology, innovation, change, digital, literacy, New Literacy Studies, disposition, Bourdieu, habitus</p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Mon, 11 Mar 2013 12:46:55 +0000</pubDate>
